text:
*
.
.
inside a bottle

anger and frustrations
disguised as hash tags
years shrunk into
hundred word updates
will social media likes
do any good?
bottled emotions
need the hammer of will
or they may remain
bottled forever.

you think i'm talking of #metoo?
no. bottled emotions never stay
limited but cover a lot
from bribe giving to bride burning
from honour killing to bullying
from ego issues to misuse
from forged to aggregated
from misplaced to misstated
the world has space for many hash tags
that must yet be born.
but until then
they remain bottled.
.
.
.
arvind passey

.

text:
did you know the autobiography behind this painting?? â€œgentileschi (1593-1653) was an exceptional artist. she was the first woman to be accepted into florenceâ€™s prestigious accademia delle arti del disegno, and caravaggioâ€™s only female follower. she was raped, when she was 17, by her painting tutor, agostino tassi. when tassi refused to marry her (the only way to restore her reputation), her father took him to court. the young gentileschi testified against her rapist and endured torture to prove her honesty. tassi was sentenced to exile, though the punishment was not enforced.

in the wake of the rape and trial, gentileschi made two paintings of judith cutting off her enemyâ€™s head. both are intensely physical, and the second is especially gory; you can almost feel the resistance of flesh to blade. scholars have noted that judith looks a lot like gentileschi, and holofernes a lot like tassi, making the paintings self-portraits of a rape victimâ€™s revenge. during and after the kavanaugh confirmation hearings â€” in which the judge denied dr. fordâ€™s accusations against him â€” people shared images of the artworks with and without comment. beyond the rage was a hunger for interpretations of sexual assault from the point of view of survivors.â€ excerpt from female artists are grappling with sexual violence in their work by @jilnotjill in the @nytimes #femaleartists #rape #metoo #artemisiagentileschi #nytimes #artreview #bmoreart

why #metoo is bullshit series

episode 1 - renuka jain, the woman all men deserve!! (check her tweets) 
the only good thing that #metoo has done is provide a powerful and effective platform for all women to speak about their unfortunate encounters with abusive men. but it's doing more harm than good to the society as women are misusing this privilege and casually calling in molestation, harassment, rape just to take revenge on their male counterparts because they got offended for some silly reason. it's not only spoiling the lives of the accused men but also making men think twice before engaging in a conversation or interaction with any woman. i think the movement is good but it needs laws against false allegations and shouldn't be biased completely towards women, there should be proper investigation before the society and media defame men immediately upon accusation. #metoo is only gonna help if the women who actually need it are able to reap its benefits. @raftaarmusic

text:
hi my name is sandra and i am a victim. i was brutally beaten & raped by my biological father when i was 14 years old. things like this are hard for people to talk about but they need to be talked about. our black community needs to address these issues. i'm 45 & this, affects my life today. i make sure i reach out to victims & lend them my ear. i let them know they are not alone. i kept it bottled up for years. but i share my story now with people to let them know yes it's happening & no you do not have to go through it alone. families need to stop sweeping this type of thing under the rug & acting like it didn't happen.
. . . 
if anyone ever needs to talk no judgement here. hit my dm. we can chat there, via cell phone, skype, etc. i'm here to listen. 
@regran_ed from @rilmello -  expose they a$$ . . .

text:
dear nirbhaya,

it has been six years since you left us with a void, an inner question, and scream. a question that we ask amongst ourselves about that dreaded night of december 16th. a scream of angst against the baseless societal norms that sill haven't changed till date.

it has been six years and still, hundreds like you plead to be saved and have their cases pending or either dead. you were a voice, a voice to the blind and dumb nation that overlooked what it meant to be a girl.

you were an inspiration, a ray of hope, a fire inside every heart....you were a revolution. you taught us that we cannotÂ take this victimization anymore, this sexualisation anymore.

it has been six years and we haven't recovered of everything that happened past your demise. we haven't forgotten you, brave heart. we haven't forgotten your sacrifice and the question that you left with u.

your untimely death was not a message but a fire that still ignite when we hear....it was a case which could have happened to any normal delhi girl.

it has been six years and you did teach us that this was not about you, it was a message that you left with us "that i want to be there, amongst all of you.live alike all of you."it was you who set that and it was you who fought back when the accident happened..sorry this wasn't an accident, this was a real bullshit done knowingly.

for us, rape of a five-year-old, sixty-year-old or a passenger in an uber are all harsh reminders of brutality that you faced.

it has been six years and you have done so much for us. many of us may not realize this, but you my beloved were a voice for all of us.

stalking, voyeurism, harassing came recognized as crimes against all of us. it is not an idea of fun picking up a woman and do anything with her.

it has been six years and you educated all of us without books- no matter how horrendous the abuse be; we cannot afford to be quiet. no matter if they call an abuse a stigma on us, we have to speak up.

we are not objects, we have a choice and we have a freedom to choose.

it has been six years and still the calls on "100" ring every second.
.
.
.
Â©vanshika @vanshika_dance

text:
not everyone knows this, but i'm kind of existentially sad most of the time, and it can be hard to see the value in anything when the world feels grey and numb and i'm too absorbed in the noise of my mind. but sometimes it's just the little things that can ground you, like a leaf on the ground that lends a splash of colour, or a dancing ray of light. i missed mental health awareness week by a bit, but some of us live needing that every week and every day. so i encourage everyone to remember what they need, and to be unashamed of asking if they need help finding it. i'm working on myself too, and i'm always here to talk <3 .
.
.
#endthestigma #mentalhealthawareness #selfcare #metoo #mentalillness #yourenotalone #life #soitgoes #littlethingsmatter

text:
no coffee at pullman.

i reached the hotel fifteen minutes before the press launch of a couple of low priced phones from @asusindia and the time was around twelve. i was asked by the pr present to have tea or coffee as there were a few minutes still before the press conference began.

so i strolled over to where a guy was fiddling with the coffee machine and asked for a serving. he turned and said, 'coffee is closed for now sir. will be served after lunch.' what? i thought. no coffee or tea? what if i don't want lunch? what is all i want is just one strong cup of coffee? but the guy just stood there and repeated, 'no sir. no coffee or tea. counter is closed.' well, all i could do then was to click a couple of pictures of cups waiting for the counter to open. the fancy painted kettle is obviously empty. and, by the way, had some women said no as firmly as the guy at the coffee counter, we might never have had this #metoo creating tsunamis today.

#coffee #tea @pullmanhotels @asus #story #hotelmanagement #hotellobby

text:
sister mary aquinas has seen some shit -
pen and ink and a tiny bit of acrylic on bristol 11x14-
each character i paint has a life of their own. i don't plan or use models, but listen and look look look as i work, and i come to know what they want, who they are, what is needed.  sister m. aquinas remains mysterious to me. i'm not sure if she's regarding something present (like, "i'm going to keep an eye on that priest") or if she's looking blankly into the past (like, "me too").
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
the lets talk about our psychic gifts ladies!!! we are all born psychic. just like we are all born emotional. but unlike emotions, most of us never had the chance to cultivate our gifts. we were most likely were born into families and a society that couldn't foster our psychic growth, probably beacuse they never fostered their own psychic growth. 
but being psychic is a huge part of what makes us women. we have used words like intuition, gut feelings, 'a sense' to describe what is an inherent gift we all have. 
we are all psychic.

the witches of the past knew this truth and spent much of their time developing, honing and practicing their psychic abilities. that is why the villagers would come to them as a spiritual leader and kings would ask for foresight into battles. 
i've spent many years developing my own psychic gifts. i am no means a master psychic but i feel very strongly called to help all women re-align themselves with their own psychic abilities. as part of my vision for the witch + womb website (release date halloween 2018) i will be offering workshops and meditations for developing your own psychic senses so you can have greater control and power in your own life. if you'd like to be a part of this and learn more, please comment below!

text:
pia camilâ€™s â€œbara bara baraâ€ approximates the makeshift tented markets of latin american urban landscapes and occupied the heart of fair market. in an entirely new configuration from its previous iterations. the work is created by sewing together hundreds of used t-shirts that have made their ways back and forth across the us/ mexico borderâ€”arriving for sale in las torres market in iztapalapa, a neighborhood of mexico city, to be bought and integrated into this artwork which has now traveled over much of the united states. the apparel utilized in this work reminds of the way that text-based messaging and slogans transmit ideas across borders to become absorbed within cultural manifestations.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
last december during miami art week, @anthony_spinello and @zoelukov curated the first in a series of alternative art fairs, entitled â€œfair.â€ fair., an alternative non-commercial art fair that took place december 7-10, 2017 at brickell city centre, served as a platform for a diverse and multigenerational group of women artists. fair. seeked to address gender inequality in the art world and beyond by providing space for radical women artists to create site-specific interventions in a non-traditional venue.

fair. was generously supported by swire properties inc, in partnership with the john s. and james l. knight foundation. â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

text:
dear someone,
i have so many questions that i want to ask you but i just don't know how? and because i know for a fact that my voice would break and tears would start streaming down my face if i were to ask you in person, and that's why i am writing you this letter. furthermore, i don't think that you would even listen to me. these days you seem to be ignoring me as if i'm your worst enemy.

how?
that would be my first question. how was it so easy for you to go? to just leave me and not even look back.

why?
why would you leave and why would you leave like that? no explanation, no real goodbye, nothing.

was it even real? what we had, i mean, was it? because i've been dreaming so much about you lately that it seems like i can't tell what's real and what's not anymore.

love, i wish you didn't shatter my heart. i wish you didn't make all these promises just to break them. i wish that you could have been honest with me from the beginning. honest about your intentions and your feelings for me.

the last time we were standing in front of each other, looking into your brown eyes made my knees go weak and my heart beat faster. how can someone feel so much and other just not? i guess i'll never know because i tend to give people all of me. always. and with you, it was no different. i gave you all of me, made you my favourite person in this shitty world and hoped that i would be your favourite too.

this is farewell, my love. i hope that a part of you never forgets me. no matter how important i really was to you. i hope that where life take you, it takes you someplace happy. you deserve it, i'm sure of that.
.
.
ananya sharma.
(@afflictionwrites)
.
.

text:
a question of leadership. fundamentally leadership is a skill. but like all skills it takes practice to get it right. it also takes a commitment to continual development, training and improvement.
identifying those leadership traits in others that impact positively and negatively on you, the team, the department and the organisation is often where we begin when developing our own leadership style â€“ taking snippets of styles of others to cultivate our own approach. how would we cope in these situations? how would we handle things differently?
is a great starting point.
.
.

text:
#metoo
an opinion piece by @bharatkhandelwal_
---
in india #metoo movement triggered with tanushree dutta's allegations on nana patekar and it grew on social media with the utsav chakraborty case in which aib was attacked and tanmay bhatt had to step down. i believe social media (sm) is a great platform to express your views and portray you talent. i never expected that sm could be used for empowerment and it would have so much effect. right now #metoo movement is at its peak in india, there are several women sharing their stories even of a 20 year old harrassment case has been shared. in #metoo movement women have not only laid allegations on men infact women has laid allegations of sexual harrassment against other women also, for example the kaneez surka- aditi mittal case. one very big victory in the ongoing time is the resignation of union minister mj akbar over sexual harrassment allegations. i also concerned here of cases in which men are wrongly attacked by women just to use their name and fame, such things should be looked upon carefully. now women has got so much power to #speakup
---
@bharatkhandelwal_

text:
#metoo
reader's opinion by suchandana patoa (@always.precise)
---
in my opinion, #metoo was an important movement. very important rather. in india, it is difficult to speak up against those who are rich and powerful, and the police often ignores such cases and judiciary takes its own time to provide justice. #metoo was also important for those who were scared to speak about the atrocities they had to face. #metoo also played an important role in making women realize that harassment, of any sort, be it be mental, physical or sexual, is not to be tolerated.

but what upsets me today is the fact that #metoo has lost its essence. in some cases, it is difficult to understand the matter and take a side. and that is bad. the movement was to empower women, but if it has reached a point where we dont know who to believe, it's indeed bad.

its difficult to find out who is honest and who is taking advantage of the movement. after all, when i decided to become a feminist, i promised myself to treat both the gender equally. 
noting that, i hope no woman or man has to go through bad experiences. no one is accused of something they didn't do and no one is subjected to victim shaming.
---
don't forget to read the other opinions on this topic and do tell us whether you agree or disagree in the comments below!

---
what is #metoo? it is a long due explosion of relevations that earlier succumbed to the fear of becoming a  social pariah and facing oppression, rather than support. it has brought out the epidemic level of toxic male chauvinism that had engulfed workplaces and homes.

agreed, there may be a few fake cases as well but loss of hair doesn't mean that you won't get chemotherapy. we need to focus on the greater good, uplifting woman and taking public morality to more appropriate levels. this is significant because when those making inappropriate actions are not taken to task, they are rather motivated to continue doing so. the current phase is the spark, what matters is that it leads to a more intense fire, the pavitra agni which cleanses minds and souls.
---

catch suzanne hannau, mika allison, jennifer woodrum, airan wright, and elliot andreano cobb perform alexis baconâ€™s capriccio in just 2 days!!! from the composer: i began writing â€œcapriccioâ€ in fall of 2008, at the time that the u.s. banking system nearly collapsed. in the media were dire warnings that we were in unprecedented, historical times, even as the sun was shining and most life continued normally. as i was composing, i kept thinking of germany in the 1920s during the weimar republic, when the arts blossomed while the country underwent a period of rapid inflation and political instability. i imagined circus and cabaret music.

we have to start talking about black women being killed by their partners. 
according to the cdc, #blackwomen killed in intimate partner homicides are 2x as likely to be killed a spouse and 4x more likely to be killed by a bf/gf than white women. 
brittney silvers was a 27 yo sergeant in the army who was killed by her estranged husband at ft. campbell on sunday night. the couple was in the middle of divorce proceedings and although there was a restraining order in place,  he returned to her home, kicked down the door and fired shots killing brittney and another harming another victim. 
#protectblackwomen

text:
with the #metoo campaign currently going around, i feel like i need to share something. i believe you like me, a survivor of childhood sexual abuse, there is something you can do to help you on your journey to heal. 
the younique foundation offers a free retreat to survivors of childhood sexual abuse. they don't force younique products on you, they don't even use our products in the makeover and photoshoot because they don't want there to be even an ounce of room for someone to say they have the wrong intentions. this foundation has one purpose, and one purpose only: to help you heal. 
no business. no sales. nothing except opportunities for you to rediscover your self-worth and heal. you are powerful beyond measure. 
i just finally took the leap and signed myself up!

if you want to know more, please check out www.youniquefoundation.org, where you can read more and apply to attend the retreat or contact me. 
#nomore1in4 #bethevoice #wewillrise #bethechange #sexualabuse #sexualabusesurvivor #lynnvaughan #makemanyripples

text:
it's is said that goddess durga annihilated the buffalo demon mahishasura and veered off his head using a trishool (given to her by lord shiva) on navami, the final day of navratris and durga puja celebrations. 
mahishasura is important in hindu scriptures since maa durga was born in order to slay him. therefore, his story is an important part of shaktism which venerates maa durga. according to hindu scriptures, mahishasura was a combination of both an asura and a mahisha (water buffalo) with trident. he intended to annihilate all the devas and gods since they were the arch-enemies of asuras. 
rambha, the king of asuras, was enticed with the beauty of a buffalo and eventually married her. the child who was born from this bestial union was named mahishasura, because he was half-buffalo and half-human (mahisha literally means buffalo). as an asura, mahishasura wanted to wage war against the devas, who were the asuras' arch-enemies. to make himself invincible mahishasura performed austerities to brahma and asked to be granted immortality. brahma refused him the boon of immortality and instead gave him a boon such that his death would happen only at the hands of a woman. mahishasura imagined that this was the equivalent of immortality, since he believed it was impossible for a woman to slay a person of his strength. emboldened by this belief, he started a war with the devas. in the battle that ensued, the devas, led by indra, were defeated. at this point the devas approached the trinity of lord shiva, brahma and shri vishnu to seek help. the three great gods combined their divine energies and created a woman. the goddess thus created was maa durga. maa durga led a battle against mahishasura and killed him, thus fulfilling the prophecy that he would meet his death at the hands of a woman.!

october is #domesticviolenceawareness month. 
let's define domestic violence. it's a pattern of abusive behavior used by a partner to gain or maintain control over the other intimate partner. it affects men, women, and children. 
for help or if you just need someone to talk to please call:
1-800-799-safe(7233)Â in more than 200 languages.Â all calls are free and confidential.

text:
okay,so one of my friends shruti,wrote this and i could not resist myself from sharing it with you all as it is so so beautiful!! i would love if you take out some time to read it and appreciate it as this really deserves it;) and shruti please keep blessing us with your writings thanks for sharing it with meâ¤ï¸ he is the colour of my mind. 
everything i think,  is stained with him 
my days, my nights 
each breath,  each tear
he's impanted in every fragment of my soul
in  ways i can't remove....
because, it would be like ripping me off-
from myself

he is the beat of my heart. 
no second passes, without him on my mind. 
guess that's the only place he can be truly mine,
in my mind. 
in corners of my heart, the places only i know. 
it's like love knocked on my door, 
and disappeared before i opened.  like cinderella went to ball, but then,
 the next day her prince didn't want her. 
like snow white  died with poison on her lips
but no prince ever came. 
like beauty and the beast. 
except, well he was a beast. 
a beast. 
he was my forever. 
that lasted only for a minute. -@shruti._.13

text:
comission (kind of?) for @floggingfuckboys
read right to left (manga)

sorry i couldn't make the upload the day i said i would^^ (ahh, the stress of a moving)

but here it is. based on the ig-story where she wrote about this depicted scenario (i asked if i could draw it) as a dream she had because of the kavanaugh-scandal. 
it was quite fun to make this and use my markers again (which i hadn't for a long time now) but i noticed that the ink i used for the outlines wasn't quite marker-durable (you betrayed me, my dear ink). so the journey in search of a water-and markerproof ink continues. 
also my comissions are open son i will make a post about it. hopefully. you know me...
just send me a dm. 
enjoy.

#manga #comic #marker #copic #ink #commission #illustration #feminism #dontmansplainourtraumatous #consentculture #metoo #antirapeculture

text:
with the #metoo campaign currently going around, i feel like i need to share something. if you are a survivor of childhood sexual abuse, there is something you can do to help you on your journey to heal. 
the younique foundation offers a free retreat to survivors of childhood sexual abuse. they don't force younique products on you, they don't even use our products in the makeover and photoshoot because they don't want there to be even an ounce of room for someone to say they have the wrong intentions. this foundation has one purpose, and one purpose only: to help you heal. 
no business. no sales. nothing except opportunities for you to rediscover your self-worth and heal. you are powerful beyond measure. 
if you want to know more, please check out www.youniquefoundation.org, where you can read more and apply to attend the retreat or contact me. 
#nomore1in4 #reclaimhope #ibelieveyou

text:
heres the reality, noones to busy 
this is coming from someone who works 18 hour days, travels out of the country and has 100s of people to email or call back. 
difference is those that are a priority i get back to sooner . i never want those that are important to feel less than or feel they have no relevance in my life.
ive had people in my life who gave me excuses for not getting back to me or doing something promised but truth is even though they maybe a priority to me i am nothing more than an excuse to them.
excuses (lies) are reasons to keep a bad behavior going, gives the person a off the hook sonto speak w a manipulation lie so they think but doesn't deal w the hurts they cause. 
just like a i'm sorry but you made me do it. another lie each person is responsible for their own behavior

text:
why i vote 
_____________________
as we approach midterms elections in the us, i canâ€™t help but sit with the emotions iâ€™ve been feeling since november 8, 2016! 
_____________________
anger at the finagling seeing the truth of our nation; fear that comes and goes as i watch how the country is being led; guilt for not being more conscious and aware; sadness at how many people have suffered directly and indirectly as a result of this administration; and hopelessness that it could ever be changed! 
_____________________
but despite these feelings, i still vote! i vote because i know my voice has to be heard and deserves to be heard. i vote because the alternative is to do nothing, and i refuse to do nothing. i vote because itâ€™s one way to show up and be seen! and, i vote because if i donâ€™t how can i complain that things arenâ€™t changing. 
_____________________ 
i know that it can feel daunting to be educated on whatâ€™s going on. and iâ€™m a huge advocate for taking care of yourself. but, donâ€™t allow apathy and fatigue stop you from being heard - and know that in voting you are taking care of yourself! || i donâ€™t tell anyone who or what to vote for. however, i will encourage you to think of not just yourself and your family, but also your neighbors, your community, families whose lives will change with your vote, people whoâ€™s rights will be stripped away with your vote, and hearts that will be broken with your vote. 
_____________________
itâ€™s not just about who/what you vote for - itâ€™s about the world that you want you and your family to live in! âœ”ï¸ register! âœ”ï¸ vote! ğŸ‘ğŸ¾ and do so every opportunity you get!! || #vote #support #midtermelections #2018midterms #metoo #lovetrumpshate #ibelieveher

text:
it is really satisfying to see so many women rise up, strongly against the torture, pain and humiliation they have faced.
#metoo
it's not just a movement. it's a revolution. but how real is this movement? 
it needs great courage to stand up against someone who has power and shout to the society *proving* that you have been a victim.so many rising brows, asking "why were you quiet then?", "you only want fame and publicity?"...when a woman decides to take a stand so many questions, judgments, pulling her down.
women against women, is the harsh reality of our hypocrite society.
so many instances..
1. ironically, in  the sabarimala case the only justice against women worship at the temple was a female "indu malhotra" where the other three male justice approved right to equlaity over irrational religious beliefs.
2. so many women have used this #metoo movement for their personal gains.where the real victims have been unable to reach out to the world, some women find peace in blaming celebrities to attract attention. showing some flirtious texts seeking justice? so many men flirt with women, infact most of the new generation relationships start with flirtful texts.and a girl always has options of blocking or drawing limits in those cases.an assault is much different from such cases.ira trivedi on the other hand is spoiling her own and chetan bhagat's life with her senseless stories.so is a random flirty statement counted as assault? did it really make you uncomfortable?
3. there have been many stories coming up against tv actors.what i am surprised of is, why are the male colleagues not speaking up? what are they afraid of? why can't they support their female friends at this time where their one statement would change the perspective of public towards that woman?
but what bothers me more is people trolling the women who are in search of their own voice.
continued in comment

text:
i wonder, have i been looking at the wrong parts of my childhood? yes, the negative had an effect but by looking for the broken pieces are we ignoring the light from those very same experiences? 
what if the gift is, that i grew up slow. isnâ€™t that a beautiful thing? to be so sheltered. to be so protected. when i saw myself as broken my internal story changed to reflect the tarnished pieces over the beauty and innocence of my childhood. 
i am blessed for not having my innocence stripped away as a child. when trauma happened, it was by a person who was rather clueless themself. thatâ€™s a gift. a gift so many other people are denied. i did choose my first time. it was not romantic, but there was choice and responsibility. that is something. 
i am blessed to have walked in the darkness for it gave me understanding of the tricks our minds play, when allowed. as a teen i was over being the good kid, i wanted a taste of darkness and i created it. it was my choice to find a new crowd. it was my choice to drink the drinks and consume the substances. i was looking for fucked up stories and i found them. i am grateful for half memories, somethings are best left forgotten. 
the tension in my soul is much older than this body. this ache in my jaw comes from generations of maternal lineage being silenced. my purpose, and i believe our generations purpose, is to clear the baggage of ages gone by. 
we are here to shift the tide. 
we only become equals by recognizing our own truth and sharing it to inspire the next voice. 
#metoo #shareyourvoice #paintingsbydana #morningmeditation #journalthenpaint

text:
baggage

in order to survive trauma, we box-up our experience and lock it away somewhere deep inside us. that compartmentalization is the only way to move forward in a functional way but the trauma is never gone. we carry it with us. we carry with us the damage, the byproducts, an altered self and the underlying fear - though it is mostly invisible. --------- #metoo #baggage #invisible #tiakeoart #sculpture #copper

text:
human beings can be so incredibly annoying. i personally don't like to be busy.

i like to go at a very slow pace in life. that's my natural pace. when people have asked me how am i doing and i say unfortunately i'm busy, they said that's good... that's good that you're busy.

no it's not. busy-ness is a fallacy. busyness is a result of a high-tech world that has gotten out of control. hi tech, coffee ridden. -------------------------------------------------------------------------

text:
12 elderly women stood nude in front of the army headquarters in imphal, manipur to protest the rape and murder of a 32 year old woman in custody. this book is a compilation of the life stories of these twelve women. 
what is most striking about these women is that they are very ordinary women. their schedules and identities are defined by their spouses, children and grand children. and yet, amidst the demands of daily life, they have set aside some time for themselves, for women, for the betterment of their society. they are the meira paibis (the torch bearers of manipur) and we have a ton to learn from their life stories, not just the single protest that made them notorious. 
one of the women is quoted to have said â€œonce we are out of the house and are with women, we donâ€™t care about our family and mundane affairs. ours is a community in itself. we donâ€™t care what husbands, sons or daughters-in-law would think. we feel empowered to take our own decision.â€ a heart warming ray of feminism from one of the darkest corners of our country. 
#mothersofmanipur #teresarehman #indianliterature #metoo #womenprotests #feminism #womenempowerment #socialactivism #manipur #northeastindianliterature #manipurliterature #nonfiction #indiannonfiction

text:
so many humans are asking me, â€œwhat is this iahsay movement?â€ well, in the same week that my dad chose to end his own life, the world took on a new american president & through all iâ€™ve seen and experienced in my youth, this was still one of the most challenging times of my life. 
our â€i am human | so are you" is a movement brought to you by the #nonprofit @essensha_ .

at essensha we focus on authentic acceptance and connection with other beings through the awareness that we are all humans being on this beautiful and incredible planet. that we are all connected through heart center and hold abilities of so much more than most of us are fully aware of. 
these bodies are mysteriously adaptive, agile, curiously strong, brilliantly healing, and yet simultaneously we are extremely vulnerable and fragile. our brains are equally fascinating, if not more - to me, and so here we all are; separated by vessels yet connected by soul, spirit, and heart center.

text:
âš  potentially triggering âš 

talking with a friend this morning about a challenge her and i both have. i want to share with you in hopes that if you have the same issue, it may be helpful. â€¢
â€¢
almost my entire life i have had stiff, tight shoulders. massage therapist always ask if i'm stressed but 9 times out of 10, i am not. 
so where are these 'knots' coming from?â€¢ â€¢
sometimes it is sinus or hormonal triggers, but not always. â€¢
â€¢
a few weeks ago i realized i always hold my shoulders high. every photo shoot the photographer has to say, 'drop your shoulders.' after some reflection and throwing the question to the universe i realize it is me 'puffing myself up'. like a cat ready to fight. in order to look larger/stronger. â€¢
â€¢
after a childhood with a violent father, not so friendly neighborhood, a family member who molested me, tried to rape me (i fought him off and was able to escape), a boss who forced himself on me ... all before 16, moving forward into adulthood working at a club with countless disrespectful men that i also sometimes had to physically fight, i lived in a constant state of survival mode. ready to fight anyone, no matter how much larger than my 4' 11" they were. in turn, my shoulders were/are always pulled up causing tension and sometimes headaches, turning into a ball of stiffness that often takes two painful deep tissue massages in a row to even begin to loosen up. â€¢
â€¢
i am currently working on consciously dropping my shoulders. telling myself i am no longer in danger. i don't have to fight anymore. this will take some time but i can tell it's working. â€¢
â€¢
ptsd is not just a mental side affect. our body also takes on the traits it needed to survive long after the trauma unless we consciously speak to it. â€¢
â€¢
allow the beast to take a rest. it isn't going anywhere. you can call upon it when truly needed. â€¢
â€¢
â€¢
â€¢

text:
â€œu.s. secretary of state mike pompeo arrived in saudi arabia on tuesday to discuss the disappearance and presumed murder of journalist jamal khashoggi with crown prince mohammed bin salman. that same day, the u.s. government received a $100 million payment from the oil-rich kingdom, the new york times and washington post reported â€” an amount that had earlier been promised to the trump administration to support its stabilization efforts in syria.

trump officials have insisted the timing of the hefty transfer was pure coincidence. but some middle eastern experts say they arenâ€™t so sure. â€œin all probability, the saudis want trump to know that his cooperation in covering for the khashoggi affair is important to the saudi monarch,â€ joshua landis, director of the university of oklahomaâ€™s center of middle east studies, told the post. â€œmuch of its financial promises to the u.s. will be contingent on this cooperation.â€ one u.s. official involved in syria policy was blunter. â€œthe timing of this is no coincidence,â€ the official told the times.

brett mcgurk, the u.s. envoy to the coalition fighting the islamic state, has maintained, however, that the saudi payment had no connection whatsoever to pompeoâ€™s meeting with the crown prince or khashoggiâ€™s alleged murder.

saudi arabia had publicly committed the money in august, he said, adding that â€œthe specific transfer of funds has been long in process and has nothing to do with other events or the secretaryâ€™s visit.â€ â€œ
.

text:
my dear brothers and sisters, 
i know i have been away for a while.
between postpartum depression, losing my cousin on february 14th in parkland, the #metoo movement- i have been fighting hard to find positivity and a proper way to regain my normalcy.  i #belivesurvivors, because #metoo, i am a survivor.

this leads me to where i do find hope- i find hope every day in the millions out there that are striving so hard to restore morals and common sense to our government. i don't care what political party you are from, or who you voted for- now is your chance to help make a change- a real impact that will guide our country forward. 
i am here, writing today to all my fellow americans. i am urging every single one of you to go vote on nov 6! in some states, early voting has already begun! 
vote for my cousin jaime, who lost her life in parkland.
vote for common sense gun safety. 
vote for the women. 
vote for the children
vote because #blacklivesmatter 
vote for our lbgtq friends and family. 
vote for healthcare.
vote for our rights to be safe.
vote to keep our democracy! 
vote to show we will not tolerate hate!
vote so we dont end up ruining the lives of our youth!
vote because your lives and rights depend on it!

we are who "they" work for- its time for our voices to be heard.

spread the word, and stop the hate. 
love and light. 
samantha

text:
#whyme ?

#
our mindset is strange ! if  a man slaps a woman ,we say he is really cruel ! if a woman slaps a man , we still say that a  man must have only done something wrong ! he deserves it ! in all the circumstances a  man is to be blamed ! i m not saying  every girl on the planet is wrong ! but there are some who really misuse their rights for personal benefits ! 
#
i respect girls but when there is a misuse of an opportunity and a man is still to be blamed i have an objection ! 
#
i don't have a real sister ,maybe i can't relate to the problems a girl has to face ! but i have a real brother!i can relate to his problems very well .since i had to get him out of them and i know how difficult it was for me ! i have a question for my female friends - if a girl accuses your real brother ,and you know he is  right ! would you protect his dignity or favour the girl ,just becos she is a girl ?

#
our mindset also says , take from one hand ,give from another! so girls , if u really want respect ,you must learn to respect as well !

text:
image credit : @iramchatrapathi thank you so much for the image.

while we all are busy sticking metaphor of the goddess to the female counterpart of our society, we conveniently choose to ignore a fact that she's equally a human and a devotee.

saddened by the incidences at #sabarimala temple, this poem is a narrative of a one sided conversation between a woman who's madly in love with the dear god.

text:

a change.org petition posted last week urged festival officials to remove bryant from the jury, according to variety, a festival sponsor. the petition claimed that keeping him on would set a â€œprecedentâ€ of leniency for sexual criminals and â€œundermine the visibility and respectâ€ that victims deserve.

eric beckman, the ceo of gkids, the company that organized the animation is film festival, announced that bryant would be removed from the jury after holding discussions with festival stakeholders. #letschat should #kobebryant still be faced with the scrutiny of his allegations from 2003? #consciouskingdom #kobebryant #bryant #timesup #metoo #metoomovement

text:
superstars durgeshwari(chhutki) & bhuneshwari(jyoti), overjoyed and pissed me off in equal amounts during my time in mp. this pms, as i brim with emotion, i feel so much love for my little ones so far away. i hope they never have to face a #metoo day in their life. i'm scared for all the little girls and younger women i dearly love; scared for the pain they're being taught to repress, for when it comes out we are nothing but an open wound. have this mamma bear feeling that makes me want to protect them all, but i don't know how. genuine doubt. any thoughts and suggestions?
#phoolkalifoundation

this one is for the women. âœ¨ the women who have suffered silently at the hands of men who exploit, abuse, and misuse them.
âœ¨ the women who have fought long and hard to raise up their communities against a society that was structured to benefit the majority, and push aside the rest.

text:
"you deserve a love that wants you disheveled, with everything and all the reasons that wake you up in a haste, with everything and the demons that won't let you sleep.
you deserve a love that makes you feel secure, able to take on the world when it walks behind you, that feels your embraces are perfect for its skin.
you deserve a love that wants to dance with you, that goes to paradise every time it looks into your eyes and never gets tires of studying your expressions.
you deserve a love that listens when you sing, that supports you when you act like a fool, that respects your freedom; that accompanies you when you fly and isn't afraid to fall.
you deserve a love that takes away the lies and brings you illusion, coffee, and poetry." ~ #fridakahlo

text:
i saw you,
i cared for you,
you found few mistakes,
and you left me. 
without arguments,
without reconciliation,
not knowing whether i am in pain or happiness. 
letting you go is hard,
but a caged bird never sings,
probably you will come back or you won't,
what matters is there was a friend who stood with you,
not anymore.

pia camilâ€™s â€œbara bara baraâ€ approximates the makeshift tented markets of latin american urban landscapes and occupied the heart of fair market. in an entirely new configuration from its previous iterations. the work is created by sewing together hundreds of used t-shirts that have made their ways back and forth across the us/ mexico borderâ€”arriving for sale in las torres market in iztapalapa, a neighborhood of mexico city, to be bought and integrated into this artwork which has now traveled over much of the united states. the apparel utilized in this work reminds of the way that text-based messaging and slogans transmit ideas across borders to become absorbed within cultural manifestations.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

last december during miami art week, @anthony_spinello and @zoelukov curated the first in a series of alternative art fairs, entitled â€œfair.â€ fair., an alternative non-commercial art fair that took place december 7-10, 2017 at brickell city centre, served as a platform for a diverse and multigenerational group of women artists. fair. seeked to address gender inequality in the art world and beyond by providing space for radical women artists to create site-specific interventions in a non-traditional venue.

fair. was generously supported by swire properties inc, in partnership with the john s. and james l. knight foundation.

text:
tbt...halloween 1982. 3 1/2 years old and loving life. had wonderful grandparents and mother who spoiled her....there was also a man in her mother's life who when of course waited until mom went to work introduced her to something different. her #metoo moment started at the age of 3. as she got older and with being threatened with a knife constantly it continued until she was 8. the only thing that would keep her happy was to suck her thumb. that was her safe place. if he caught her with her thumb that's when the knife came out. she finally told her mother after one last attempt was made when she was 9 and visited his mother for christmas. his mother called the girl a liar. he of course denied it. she called her mom who then picked her and her sister up. mom was more upset that she so afraid to say anything and mom was ready to get him killed. was a bossy kid and always wanted to be in charge even if that meant playing the "dad" during playtime. fast forward 30 years....still aggressive, worries about her daughter when she's not with her,  and typically gravitates to those that are older......if i could talk to this girl i wouldn't even know what to say. maybe at some point i will. be careful with who you have around your children. apparently though this happens a lot and families keep it quiet. stop it. if anyone needs help in confronting someone let me know. i will come. 
#mstqmusic #childhood #metoo #tanquerayhayward #littlegirl #beautifulgirl #innocentgirl

text:
i once told my exboyfriend i was abused as a child, it took a lot of strength to actually say it out loud. he asked a lot of questions like how old i was, what was i wearing, why did i not say anything before, was i really that dumb to sit through it repeatedly. i lost my strength i lost my love and i felt all that shame and guilt and pain once again. it's always easy to dismiss metoo stories, but the women has more to lose by coming out. 
#poems #poetsofinstagram #poetry #poetrycommunity #love #life #survivor #metoo #timesup #loss #abuse #speakup

text:
right now is a very difficult time for survivors, their experiences have been reaffirmed on the national stage. many of us have seen firsthand, the shitty traitor women who hide behind their internalized misogyny instead of facing it, or have been blamed for speaking out, and sadly, so many of us have been betrayed by cowards. you never know the trauma people carry with them as they continue through life, so be kind and be a human. 
one of my best friends, willow, is an extremely talented artist and she is a  survivor. in this debilitating darkness, i feel so priveleged to have surrounded myself with compassionate, fiercely open, and strong friends like willow. 
her artwork depicting ptsd and trauma is simple and powerful. i hope it helps someone feel a little less alone. ğŸ’œ
.
.
.

i ain't a professional photographer nor i  have those equipments but here i tried to capture the best  i could, that night there were  a plenty of shooting stars to be seen up there  each time you turn your head up there was 1 .
.
.
i've missed watching stars from my terrace and now that's one of the reason for traveling to mountains to witness this beauty of nature in its true form and no better way than riding.  right ??
.
.

text:
**workshop alert**
.
'i am unique: understanding body rights and responsibilities' .
we are pleased to share this call for registrations for a #free #workshop conducted by @anubhutitrust, within the framework of #fondle.
.
given india's #metoo movement taking place, this workshop is timely and much needed, specially designed in the hope of inspiring change during what is a very confusing time for young people. .
to register please email office@mumbaiartroom.org 
#teens #sexualhealth #metoo #consent #body #dignity #free #colaba #india

text:
actress nandita das to support me too campaign despite sexual slur against her father.
mumbai: unfazed by the disturbing sexual harassment charge against her father, noted painter jatin das, actor-director nandita das has said she will continue to lend support to the #metoo movement. â€œas a strong supporter of the #metoo movement, i want to reiterate that i will continue to add my voice to it, despite the disturbing allegations made against my father, which he has categorically denied,â€ nandita said in her facebook post. â€œi have maintained from the very start that this is the time we all need to listen, so that women (and men) feel safe to speak up. at the same time, it is also important to be sure about the allegations so as not to dilute the movement,â€ she added.

maintaining that she would continue to stand shoulder-to-shoulder with the women coming forward with stories of abuse and harassment, nandita, however, said that the women need to be sure about their allegations before accusing someone.

my bhubaneswar - share the update with your friends and relatives and shoot in some comments regarding the same - we would like to hear some more from you all.
#mybhubaneswar - share and comment

text:
this pendant was made for a girl who went from scotland to colombia to fight for women's rights. it is from my hero collection, which was designed to express that a hero is someone who sacrifices their own comforts to fight for the rights of other, often against powerful opponents. the pendant is engraved in spanish "con razon y e corazon" meaning with reason and heart. it is part of a quote that says with reason and with heart women can change the world. the other side of the pendant is set with a diamond in the rough section. 
i was commissioned to make this by the girl's mother. she wanted something her daughter could wear to remind her how proud she was of what she was doing and she felt this piece of jewellery was special and would not attract unwelcome attention from people who may want to steal something that looked valuable. my jewellery is not about status, it's about emotion, relationships and love. there is nothing of more value that knowing you have grown up to become your mother's hero â¤
#hero #mother #daughter #womensrights #metoo #columbia #women #humanrights #heart #reason #rolemodel #scotland #unforgettable #jewellery #special #different #loved #engraved #gift #travel #travelling

text:
good morning once again and welcome to the natural world history museum, year 5623. i am alexis and i will be your holographic guide for the next part of your journey. i hope you are well and have been enjoying your visit so far. we have now covered the evolution of early man up to the year 2100. in this section that we will look at the evolution of the female population specifically. you may have learnt in classrooms through history books how women were oppressed and considered second class citizens for a large part of history. even as they won independence to be at par with men, it remained mere words on paper. however, where society abandoned women, natural selection aided in allowing them to take their rightful place in the world. 
specimen 1: mulior magna bellator. locally known as magna women, these women are found in areas that once housed men who beat their wives and also engaged in marital rape. this species has evolved to grow up to 8 to 9 ft and can weigh anything from 150 to 280 kilograms. they can pick up and fling heavy objects including their male counterparts who occasionally resort to violence to meet their ends.

specimen 2: bellator clamosa. the clamsosa women are found in areas that were once unsafe for women at nights. they are set apart by the high pitched screech they emit that would instantly kill their attackers and any other goons within a 10 to 15 meter radii of the clamosa woman.

specimen 3: talpa mulior bellatoria. this is the chameleon species of the modern day woman. these species of women are found in areas where women were not only oppressed by men but other women too. the talpas quickly blend into their environment when they are caught doing anything that is deemed socially unacceptable for woman. (continued in comment)

text:
dear women (and men), to be honest i was the part of those who were in disbelief. not because i did not have faith with women who have been sharing stories of the assaults and the harassment they have faced, but because, i had so little faith in the world already, that i did not want to lose it. the past one week has been brutal. with men and women, women even more so because of the kind of experiences they have let out namely and anonymously that i can feel, quite literally their broken worlds.

while at one side i believe that there should be a clear understanding of what does sexual assault apertains to, what it constitutes of and what it doesn't; metoo campaign like a lot of other hashtags is not a trend that every woman coming out brave, to this world is following. it is in all its senses a way to put forth what wrongdoings have been faced by them under one tag. that too only for this world to pick up the scattered pieces at one place. women do not, i repeat for emphasis, do not know anyone shit and hence we get to decide when, in what day of the week and what year of the calendar do we speak about the horrifying experiences that we have had and make 'our' monsters face the world.

the stories i've read in the past few days have made me feel naked, ripped off my sanity at times and have tangled my flesh and skin together. such is the harrowing experience women have had and i'll take time to feel like myself and start living with it again.

until then, i'm saluting women who are fighting, juggling home, assignments, projects, deadlines and the shockwaves of the metoo movement around them. my heart is going out to all of you, anywhere you are in the world while you are jotting down with a continuous struggle the accounts of sexual harassment and the nude incidents that have occurred to you by those in power.

let's look forward to reparations. i am here. he is here. we are here. we are all listening and we know, we know, that this was not your fault. so keep drinking water and keep rioting.

thank you for doing what you are doing. i know what it is, i know what it feels like.

yours in believe, 
today and ten years later.
diya

text:
no trial, no evidence, no chance for the accused to explain his/her side, and everything is considered to be true once it has a following.

it has more power than the judicial system.

because it declares you guilty, wrong, and whatsoever without any hearing.

for the victims, it's a great platform to make their voice get heard which otherwise, most of the times, get suppressed. 
but it should never be the judge. it can be a platform to raise your voice, and encourage those who are suppressing their voices due to fear and embarrassment. but never be the judge.

remember the case of jasleen kaur? the accused guy is still suffering and the girl didn't show up for any hearing because she is studying abroad. because we all, the backbone of social media, had given the verdict without even listening to the accused, who might be the victim in this case.

text:
please know this! our tears create a flood that surprises noah! while many are searching for their voice... wisdom cries out loudly begging for earthlings to know her, while understanding, with her unfathomable gorgeous self, stands along with her!

james 1:5
if any of you lacks wisdom, you should ask god, who gives generously to all without finding fault, and it will be given to you.

proverbs 3:19
by wisdom the lord laid the earth's foundations, by understanding he set the heavens in place;

proverbs 1:20-21
20 out in the open wisdom calls aloud, she raises her voice in the public square; 21 on top of the wall she cries out, at the city gate she makes her speech:

proverbs 7:4
say unto wisdom, thou art my sister; and call understanding thy kinswoman:

proverbs 1:7-9
7 the fear of the lord is the beginning of knowledge: but fools despise wisdom and instruction. 8 my son, hear the instruction of thy father, and forsake not the law of thy mother: 9 for they shall be an ornament of grace unto thy head, and chains about thy neck.

revelation 21:4
and god shall wipe away all tears from their eyes; and there shall be no more death, neither sorrow, nor crying, neither shall there be any more pain: for the former things are passed away.

text:
page 2 - clear image !! after much introspection, i decided to put this up on social media howmuchever of a minor incident it was, it was appalling. how much more are we going to save ourselves at every step. it is exhausting. 
to be friendly is mistaken as an invite and to be aloof is termed as arrogance. friendship is not so easy to develop in a country like india with men, especially if a girl is looking for good work and is still an underdog. no energy for such bullshit that too for such mediocre work. so women just end up looking for moksha in a new country with better laws or just divert their attention from the reality altogether. 	i am so so happy to see this #metoo uproar and i really hope that karma serves justice to each and every man who thought that they could get away with such evil acts by misusing their position. women in india are eve teased, inappropriately touched in buses, trains and even on foot paths for godâ€™s sake and we all know that - this is the harsh reality. i also empathise with men who might have undergone similar experiences probably with powerful women/men therefore we all should come out and talk about it.
.
.
.
.

text:
"me too" movement in india envelopes odia painter

the #meetoo movement has shifted from film industry to media houses to literature industry and even the art industry now, with new allegations levelled against famous painter and padma bhusan jatin das, by activist nisha bora. odia painter jatin das is the latest celebrity to be enveloped in the #metoo movement that began in india with tanushree dutta accusing nana patekar of misconduct. the famous painter, and father of actor nandita das, has been accused of sexual assault by his former assistant, nisha bora. 
while #metoo was coined by activist tarana burke way back in 2006, the term only really gained traction following the harvey weinstein revelations of 2017 and how he sexually harassed and assaulted dozens of women. following tanushree dutta's allegations against veteran actor nana patekar and the ongoing maelstrom of accusations that have followed it, #metoo movement in india and related searches are not restricted only to urban areas but have spread across the country.

my bhubaneswar - share the update with your friends and relatives and shoot in some comments regarding the same - we would like to hear some more from you all.
#mybhubaneswar - share and comment

text:
like vodka shots we drink this night.
3 a.m. streets & cold moon bright.
we're the new tribe 
with our new crimes
of love & chase & a breathless race!
smoking eyes in the disco lights.
we fuck love, then take a lusty bite.
the genuine love we ditch on gossip
& wear the cologne of unsure friendships.
their coffee strong advice
with white washed favours,
brave loves torn & 
they become "life savers"!~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ like christmas carols we sing our woes.
on first dates we shrink to vulnerableâ€“
depression on our fingers,
anxiety under the toes.
music blaring high ov'r our beats.
& hearts die down on seeing
the 'perfect' lovers meet..
we cry our aches into some stinking basin
of #metoo by exes and cousins.

but the true ones always come back
bringing nectar to drench
our burning hells insomniac.
their warm, protective, loving arms 
erase aches, tears, anxieties
& tendencies of self harm.

surer. braver. finally the loves unite
bringing green hope with some fairy lights.
pristine, pure & platonic passions
with immortal smiles,
rejuvenated compassion.

they revive usâ€“
breathing in life!
they heal usâ€“
giving joys blithe!
and our lives, laughs, loves begin.
did you realise, they've made us humans again?
~avi~

text:
they say: â€œwhy didnâ€™t she/he leave or speak up sooner?â€
-
out of every 1,000 sexual assaults, 310 are reported to the police.
why?
because they are often caught in a web made from isolation, confidence-crushing abuse and by realistic fears of greater harm should they leave. they can also feel caught when they meet with indifference from others or, worse, insults that add to their injuries.
-
the question we should ask is â€˜why did the abuser do it?â€™ we need to put the focus on the crime, not what the victim is choosing to doâ€”or not choosing to do, as it may be out of their control. we need to ask why someone feels ok physically harming another person.â€
-
up until recent decades, it was thought that marital rape wasnâ€™t possible. rape was only considered a crime if it was committed by a stranger or by someone with whom the victim did not share an intimate relationship; there was actually an exemption written into rape laws for married couples. as a result, the first marital rape conviction in the united states didnâ€™t occur until the 1970s.
-
the reality is that whenever sexual consent isnâ€™t given and sex is forced upon someone, then rape has been committed.
sources: www.tariolaw.com, www.siumed.org

text:
we are a small design community in india. ten years ago we were a handful, and even though in the thousands today, we remain a tight-knit group. most of us working in this space know each other and have on occasion supported each other's work. since we are in this together, we have the golden opportunity to create a community built on the values we believe in, with zero tolerance for destructive behaviour.
.
often, women share that they have tolerated harassment due to fear of repercussions on their professional careers. it might be tough to know this with certainty at times, but there are lots of examples otherwise. indeed, career success is not dependant on tolerance of harassment. please know, as an option, you can reach us to discuss this: contact@borderandfall.com
.
@sanketavlani of @dsgnfbrc and @taxifabric has built a rising business over the last few years and ongoing allegations of sexual harassment have flooded the news. sanket: these are not baseless accusations against you, they are a resounding call for action. to all stakeholders / collaborators / patrons who have supported your work in the past, this is a moment of deep introspection. we are clear where we stand: with ayesha @kometjuice, swapna @nairswapna and others who have come forward.
.
